To trigger a Hangfire recurring job with a cron expression and control its activation status based on a specific datetime, you can make use of the `Cron` class provided by Hangfire. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```csharp
using Hangfire;
using Hangfire.Common;
using Hangfire.Logging;
using Hangfire.Server;
using System;

namespace HangfireDemo
{
    public class MyJobClass
    {
        public void MyRecurringJobMethod()
        {
            // Your job logic goes here
            // This method will be executed based on the cron expression
        }
    }

    public class CronJobActivator : JobActivator
    {
        public override object ActivateJob(Type jobType)
        {
            if (DateTime.UtcNow < new DateTime(2023, 12, 31, 23, 59, 59))
            {
                throw new InvalidOperationException("Job is inactive until December 31, 2023");
            }

            return base.ActivateJob(jobType);
        }
    }

    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            GlobalConfiguration.Configuration.UseActivator(new CronJobActivator());

            // Configure Hangfire with your storage provider (e.g., SQL Server, Redis, etc.)
            GlobalConfiguration.Configuration.UseSqlServerStorage("YourConnectionString");

            RecurringJob.AddOrUpdate<MyJobClass>(x => x.MyRecurringJobMethod(), Cron.Daily());

            using (var server = new BackgroundJobServer())
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Hangfire server started. Press any key to exit...");
                Console.ReadKey();
                server.Dispose();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

In the `CronJobActivator`, you can specify your own condition for activating the job based on a specific datetime. In this example, the job will be inactive until December 31, 2023. You can update the activation logic inside the `ActivateJob` method according to your requirements.

Be sure to provide your own cron expression and connection string in the code above (`Cron.Daily()` and `"YourConnectionString"` placeholders) as per your needs.

When the job is inactive, attempting to execute it will throw an exception. Once the specified datetime is reached, the job will become active and the Hangfire server will execute it based on the configured cron expression.
